03590nam a22005055i 9780300263060DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002630607 a10.12987/97803002630602doi  a(DE-B1597)672521  a(OCoLC)1414455701  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aHIS0360402bisacsh04a529.1qOCoLC223/eng/20230216  aND 6970qDE-24/22sred2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/125110:1 aHenkin, David M, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Week :bA History of the Unnatural Rhythms That Made Us Who We Are /cDavid M Henkin. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: in search of weekly time -- tChapter one. A People of the Week -- tChapter two. Our Appointed Times the rise of the modern week -- tChapter three. Does Anybody Really Know What Time It Is? -- tChapter four. Preserving the Modern Week -- tEpilogue. At week’s end? -- tAppendixes -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn investigation into the evolution of the seven-day week and how our attachment to its rhythms influences how we live “[Henkin] scours American literature, diaries, periodicals, menus and other ephemera from as far back as the 17th century to unearth fascinating evidence of the stickiness of the seven-day cycle.”—Melissa Holbrook Pierson, Wall Street Journal We take the seven-day week for granted, rarely asking what anchors it or what it does to us. Yet weeks are not dictated by the natural order. They are, in fact, an artificial construction of the modern world. With meticulous archival research that draws on a wide array of sources—including newspapers, restaurant menus, theater schedules, marriage records, school curricula, folklore, housekeeping guides, courtroom testimony, and diaries—David Henkin reveals how our current devotion to weekly rhythms emerged in the United States during the first half of the nineteenth century. Reconstructing how weekly patterns insinuated themselves into the social practices and mental habits of Americans, Henkin argues that the week is more than just a regimen of rest days or breaks from work, but a dominant organizational principle of modern society. Ultimately, the seven-day week shapes our understanding and experience of time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aTime measurements-History. 0aTime measurements. 0aWeek-History. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300263060?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300263060423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300263060/original  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles